<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-s03e03">
    <title>Episode 3: Multiplying Fractions</title>
    <assemblage>
        <title>Episode 3 Learning Goals</title>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Multiply fractions
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        “Pre-simplify” the result of a fraction multiplication through “cross-cancelling.” 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Raise fractions to powers.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </assemblage>
    <assemblage>
        <title>Episode 3 Key Terminology</title>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Cross-cancel
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </assemblage>
    <p>
        Fractions can be multiplied via the following process:
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Multiply the two numerators.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Multiply the two denominators.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Simplify the result.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <example>
        <p>
            Multiply the fractions:
            <md>
                \frac{2}{3}\times \frac{9}{10}
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Solution: We multiply the numerators together, and we multiply the denominators together:
            <md>
                \frac{2\times 9}{3\times 10} = \frac{18}{30}
            </md>
            Then, we simplify the result. Here, we notice that both 18 and 30 can be divided by 3:
            <md>
                \frac{18\div 3}{30\div 3} = \frac{6}{10}
            </md>
            We also notice that 6 and 10 can be divided by 2:
            <md>
                \frac{6\div 2}{10\div 2} = \frac{3}{5}
            </md>
        </p>
    </example>
    <assemblage>
        <title>Makes Sense, Right?</title>
        <p>
            Remember from Episode 2 that the word “of” corresponds to multiplication. So half <alert>of</alert> half of a pizza would correspond to:
            <md>
                \frac{1}{2}\times \frac{1}{2}
            </md>
            Physically, half of half of a pizza is one-quarter of a pizza:
        </p>
        <figure>
            <caption> Half of a half of a pizza is a quarter </caption>
            <image source="halfpizza.png">
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
            Mathematically,
            <md>
                \frac{1}{2}\times\frac{1}{2} = \frac{1\times 1}{2\times 2} = \frac{1}{4}
            </md>
        </p>
    </assemblage>
    <p>
       Notice that dividing by 1 has no effect on a number:
       <md>
        \frac{3}{1} = 3
       </md>
       So, if you need to multiply a fraction by a whole number, put the whole number over a denominator of 1.
    </p>
    <example>
        <p>
            Calculate the product:
            <md>
                6\times \frac{1}{2}
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Solution: Put the whole number, 6, over a denominator of 1:
            <md>
                \frac{6}{1}\times \frac{1}{2}
            </md>
            Multiply the numerators and denominators:
            <md>
                \frac{6\times 1}{1\times 2} = \frac{6}{2}
            </md>
            Then, simplify:
            <md>
                \frac{6}{2} = 3
            </md>
        </p>
    </example>

    <assemblage>
        <title>Makes Sense, Right?</title>
        <p>
            If I have 6 objects, and I want half of those 6 objects, then half of those 6 objects is 3 objects.
        </p>
    </assemblage>

    <example>
    <p>
        Calculate the value of 
        <md>
            \left(\frac{2}{2}\right)^4
        </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Remember that raising a number to the fourth power means multiplying together 4 copies of the number:
            <md>
                \frac{2}{3}\times\frac{2}{3}\times\frac{2}{3}\times\frac{2}{3}
            </md>
            We multiply the numerators and denominators:
            <md>
                \frac{2\times 2\times 2\times 2}{3\times 3\times 3\times 3} = \frac{16}{81}
            </md>
            This cannot be simplified any further, so 16/81 is our final answer.
        </p>
    </example>

    <definition xml:id="def-cross-canceling">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Cross-canceling</term>: When multiplying fractions, you can simplify your answer before multiplying the numerator and denominator.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
        <p>
            Multiply these fractions, using cross-cancelling:
            <md>
                \frac{2}{3}\times \frac{9}{10}
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Solution: Notice that the number 2 divides the first numerator and second denominator, so divide each of those by 2:
            <md>
                \frac{2\div 2}{3}\times \frac{9}{10\div 2} = \frac{1}{3}\times \frac{9}{5}
            </md>
            Notice that the number 3 divides the second numerator and the first denominator, so divide each of those by 3:
            <md>
                \frac{1}{3/div 3}\times \frac{9\div 3}{5} = \frac{1}{1}\times\frac{3}{5}
            </md>
            Now we finish the multiplication:
            <md>
                \frac{1\times 3}{1\times 5} = \frac{3}{5}
            </md>
            And we notice that the final answer is already fully simplified!
        </p>
    </example>
    <assemblage>
        <title>Be Careful</title>
        <p>
            This “cross-cancelling” trick only works when multiplying fractions. It won't work when adding, subtracting, or dividing fractions.
        </p>
    </assemblage>
    <p>
        When working with negative fractions, use the same rules for multiplying negative numbers that we learned back in Season 2.
    </p>
</section>